# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: text-to-speech-synthesis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] where $\theta$ is the set of model parameters.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] Typically, the input text will first be passed to an acoustic feature generator, then the acoustic features are passed to the neural vocoder.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] For the acoustic feature generator, the loss function is typically L1 loss (Mean Absolute Error, MAE) or L2 loss (Mean Square Error, MSE).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] These loss functions impose a constraint that the output acoustic feature distributions must be Gaussian or Laplacian.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] where ${\text{loss}}_{\text{human}}$ is the loss from human voice band and $\alpha$ is a scalar, typically around 0.5.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] The acoustic feature is typically a spectrogram or Mel scale.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] These features capture the time-frequency relation of the speech signal, and thus are sufficient to generate intelligent outputs.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] The Mel-frequency cepstrum feature used in the speech recognition task is not suitable for speech synthesis, as it reduces too much information.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] In September 2016, DeepMind released WaveNet, which demonstrated that deep learning-based models are capable of modeling raw waveforms and generating speech from acoustic features like spectrograms or mel-spectrograms.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] Although WaveNet was initially considered to be computationally expensive and slow to be used in consumer products at the time, a year after its release, DeepMind unveiled a modified version of WaveNet known as "Parallel WaveNet," a production model 1,000 faster than the original.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] This was followed by Google AI's **Tacotron 2** in 2018, which demonstrated that neural networks could produce highly natural speech synthesis but required substantial training data—typically tens of hours of audio—to achieve acceptable quality.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] Tacotron 2 used an autoencoder architecture with attention mechanisms to convert input text into mel-spectrograms, which were then converted to waveforms using a separate neural vocoder.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] When trained on smaller datasets, such as 2 hours of speech, the output quality degraded while still being able to maintain intelligible speech, and with just 24 minutes of training data, Tacotron 2 failed to produce intelligible speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] In 2019, Microsoft Research introduced **FastSpeech**, which addressed speed limitations in autoregressive models like Tacotron 2.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] FastSpeech utilized a non-autoregressive architecture that enabled parallel sequence generation, significantly reducing inference time while maintaining audio quality.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] Its feedforward transformer network with length regulation allowed for one-shot prediction of the full mel-spectrogram sequence, avoiding the sequential dependencies that bottlenecked previous approaches.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] The same year saw the release of **HiFi-GAN**, a generative adversarial network (GAN)-based vocoder that improved the efficiency of waveform generation while producing high-fidelity speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] In 2020, the release of **Glow-TTS** introduced a flow-based approach that allowed for fast inference and voice style transfer capabilities.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] In March 2020, the free text-to-speech website 15.ai was launched.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] 15.ai gained widespread international attention in early 2021 for its ability to synthesize emotionally expressive speech of fictional characters from popular media with minimal amount of data.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] The creator of 15.ai (known pseudonymously as 15) stated that 15 seconds of training data is sufficient to perfectly clone a person's voice (hence its name, "15.ai"), a significant reduction from the previously known data requirement of tens of hours.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] 15.ai is credited as the first platform to popularize AI voice cloning in memes and content creation.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] 15.ai used a multi-speaker model that enabled simultaneous training of multiple voices and emotions, implemented sentiment analysis using DeepMoji, and supported precise pronunciation control via ARPABET.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] The 15-second data efficiency benchmark was later corroborated by OpenAI in 2024.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] Currently, self-supervised learning has gained much attention through better use of unlabelled data.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] Research has shown that, with the aid of self-supervised loss, the need for paired data decreases.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] Zero-shot speaker adaptation is promising because a single model can generate speech with various speaker styles and characteristic.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] In June 2018, Google proposed to use pre-trained speaker verification models as speaker encoders to extract speaker embeddings.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] The speaker encoders then become part of the neural text-to-speech models, so that it can determine the style and characteristics of the output speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] This procedure has shown the community that it is possible to use only a single model to generate speech with multiple styles.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] In deep learning-based speech synthesis, neural vocoders play an important role in generating high-quality speech from acoustic features.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] The WaveNet model proposed in 2016 achieves excellent performance on speech quality.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] where $\theta$ is the model parameter including many dilated convolution layers.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] Thus, each audio sample $x_{t}$ is conditioned on the samples at all previous timesteps.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] However, the auto-regressive nature of WaveNet makes the inference process dramatically slow.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] To solve this problem, Parallel WaveNet was proposed.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] Parallel WaveNet is an inverse autoregressive flow-based model which is trained by knowledge distillation with a pre-trained teacher WaveNet model.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] Since such inverse autoregressive flow-based models are non-auto-regressive when performing inference, the inference speed is faster than real-time.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] Meanwhile, Nvidia proposed a flow-based WaveGlow model, which can also generate speech faster than real-time.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] However, despite the high inference speed, parallel WaveNet has the limitation of needing a pre-trained WaveNet model, so that WaveGlow takes many weeks to converge with limited computing devices.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/deep-learning-speech-synthesis] This issue has been solved by Parallel WaveGAN, which learns to produce speech through multi-resolution spectral loss and GAN learning strategies.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] In sound processing, the **mel-frequency cepstrum** (**MFC**) is a representation of the short-term power spectrum of a sound, based on a linear cosine transform of a log power spectrum on a nonlinear mel scale of frequency.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Map the powers of the spectrum obtained above onto the mel scale, using triangular overlapping windows or alternatively, cosine overlapping windows.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Take the logs of the powers at each of the mel frequencies.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Take the discrete cosine transform of the list of mel log powers, as if it were a signal.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] The MFCCs are the amplitudes of the resulting spectrum.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] There can be variations on this process, for example: differences in the shape or spacing of the windows used to map the scale, or addition of dynamics features such as "delta" and "delta-delta" (first- and second-order frame-to-frame difference) coefficients.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] The European Telecommunications Standards Institute in the early 2000s defined a standardised MFCC algorithm to be used in mobile phones.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] MFCCs are commonly used as features in speech recognition systems, such as the systems which can automatically recognize numbers spoken into a telephone.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] MFCCs are also increasingly finding uses in music information retrieval applications such as genre classification, audio similarity measures, etc.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Since Mel-frequency bands are distributed evenly in MFCC, and they are very similar to the voice system of a human, MFCC can efficiently be used to characterize speakers.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] For instance, it can be used to recognize the speaker's cell phone model characteristics, and further the details of the speaker's voice.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] This type of mobile device recognition is possible because the production of electronic components in a phone have tolerances, because different electronic circuit realizations do not have exact same transfer functions.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] The dissimilarities in the transfer function from one realization to another becomes more prominent if the task performing circuits are from different manufacturers.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Hence, each cell phone introduces a convolutional distortion on input speech that leaves its unique impact on the recordings from the cell phone.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Therefore, a particular phone can be identified from the recorded speech by multiplying the original frequency spectrum with further multiplications of transfer functions specific to each phone followed by signal processing techniques.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Thus, by using MFCC one can characterize cell phone recordings to identify the brand and model of the phone.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] As speech is not stationary signal, it is divided into overlapped frames within which the signal is assumed to be stationary.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] where *w(n)*: windowed function of length W.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Hence, as specified the footprint of mobile phone of the recorded speech is the convolution distortion that helps to identify the recording phone.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] $H(f)$ can be considered as a concatenated transfer function that produced input speech, and the recorded speech $Y_{p}w(f)$ can be perceived as original speech from cell phone.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] So, equivalent transfer function of vocal tract and cell phone recorder is considered as original source of recorded speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] where *Xew(f)* is the excitation function, $X_{v}(f)$ is the vocal tract transfer function for speech in the $p^{th}$ frame and $H'(f)$ is the equivalent transfer function that characterizes the cell phone.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] This approach can be useful for speaker recognition as the device identification and the speaker identification are very much connected.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] MFCC is successful because of this nonlinear transformation with additive property.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] where, cy(j), ce(j), cw(j) are the recorded speech cepstrum and weighted equivalent impulse response of cell phone recorder that characterizes the cell phone, respectively, while j is the number of filters in the filter bank.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] More precisely, the device specific information is in the recorded speech which is converted to additive form suitable for identification.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] cy(j) can be further processed for identification of the recording phone.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Commonly used window functions- Hamming and Hanning windows.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Hence, Mel-scale is a commonly used frequency scale that is linear till 1000 Hz and logarithmic above it.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] MFCCs are obtained by taking Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT) of the spectral envelope.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] where $c_{i}=c_{y}(i)$ corresponds to the i -th MFCC coefficient, $N_{f}$ is the number of triangular filters in the filter bank, $S_{n}$ is the log energy output of n -th filter coefficient, and L is the number of MFCC coefficients that we want to calculate.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Each step corresponds to one step in MFCC calculation.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] MFCC values are not very robust in the presence of additive noise, and so it is common to normalise their values in speech recognition systems to lessen the influence of noise.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Some researchers propose modifications to the basic MFCC algorithm to improve robustness, such as by raising the log-mel-amplitudes to a suitable power (around 2 or 3) before taking the discrete cosine transform (DCT), which reduces the influence of low-energy components.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Paul Mermelstein is typically credited with the development of the MFC.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Sometimes both early originators are cited.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/mel-frequency-cepstrum] Many authors, including Davis and Mermelstein, have commented that the spectral basis functions of the cosine transform in the MFC are very similar to the principal components of the log spectra, which were applied to speech representation and recognition much earlier by Pols and his colleagues.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] In linguistics, **prosody** (/ˈprɒsədi, ˈprɒz-/) is the study of elements of speech, including intonation, stress, rhythm and loudness, that occur simultaneously with individual phonetic segments: vowels and consonants.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Often, prosody specifically refers to such elements, known as *suprasegmentals* when they extend across more than one phonetic segment.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Prosody reflects the nuanced emotional features of the speaker or of their utterances: their obvious or underlying emotional state, the form of utterance (statement, question, or command), the presence of irony or sarcasm, certain emphasis on words or morphemes, contrast, focus, and so on.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Prosody displays elements of language that are not encoded by grammar, punctuation or choice of vocabulary.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Auditory (subjective) and objective (acoustic and articulatory) measures of prosody do not correspond in a linear way.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Most studies of prosody have been based on auditory analysis using auditory scales.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Different combinations of these variables are exploited in the linguistic functions of intonation and stress, as well as other prosodic features such as rhythm and tempo.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Additional prosodic variables have been studied, including voice quality and pausing.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] The behavior of the prosodic variables can be studied either as contours across the prosodic unit or by the behavior of boundaries.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Prosodic features are suprasegmental, since they are properties of units of speech that are defined over groups of sounds rather than single segments.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Personal characteristics that belong to an individual are not linguistically significant while prosodic features are.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Prosody has been found across all languages and is described to be a natural component of language.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] The defining features of prosody that display the nuanced emotions of an individual differ across languages and cultures.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Some writers (e.g., O'Connor and Arnold) have described intonation entirely in terms of pitch, while others (e.g., Crystal) propose that "intonation" is a combination of several prosodic variables.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] The exchange above is an example of using intonation to highlight particular words and to employ rising and falling of pitch to change meaning.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] If read out loud, the pitch of the voice moves in different directions on the word "cat." In the first line, pitch goes up, indicating a question.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] In the second line, pitch falls, indicating a statement‍— a confirmation of the first line in this case.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Finally, in the third line, a complicated fall-rise pattern indicates incredulity.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Each pitch/intonation pattern communicates a different meaning.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] An additional pitch-related variation is *pitch range*; speakers are capable of speaking with a wide range of pitch (this is usually associated with excitement), while at other times with a narrow range.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] English makes use of changes in *key*; shifting one's intonation into the higher or lower part of one's pitch range is believed to be meaningful in certain contexts.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Stress functions as the means of making a syllable prominent.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Stress may be studied in relation to individual words (named "word stress" or lexical stress) or in relation to larger units of speech (traditionally referred to as "sentence stress" but more appropriately named "prosodic stress").
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Stressed syllables are made prominent by several variables.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Some of these cues are more powerful or prominent than others.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Alan Cruttenden, for example, writes "Perceptual experiments have clearly shown that, in English at any rate, the three features (pitch, length and loudness) form a scale of importance in bringing syllables into prominence, pitch being the most efficacious, and loudness the least so".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] When pitch prominence is the major factor, the resulting prominence is often called *accent* rather than stress.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] There is considerable variation from language to language concerning the role of stress in identifying words or in interpreting grammar and syntax.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Although rhythm is not a prosodic variable in the way that pitch or loudness are, it is usual to treat a language's characteristic rhythm as a part of its prosodic phonology.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] As explained in the isochrony article, this claim has not been supported by scientific evidence.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Voiced or unvoiced, the pause is a form of interruption to articulatory continuity such as an open or terminal juncture.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Conversation analysis commonly notes pause length.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Distinguishing auditory hesitation from silent pauses is one challenge.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Contrasting junctures within and without word chunks can aid in identifying pauses.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] There are a variety of "filled" pause types.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Formulaic language pause fillers include "Like", "Er" and "Um", and paralinguistic expressive respiratory pauses include the sigh and gasp.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Although related to breathing, pauses may contain contrastive linguistic content, as in the periods between individual words in English advertising voice-over copy sometimes placed to denote high information content, e.g.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Pausing or its lack contributes to the perception of word groups, or chunks.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Examples include the phrase, phraseme, constituent or interjection.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Chunks commonly highlight lexical items or fixed expression idioms.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Chunking prosody is present on any complete utterance and may correspond to a syntactic category, but not necessarily.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] The well-known English chunk "Know what I mean?" in common usage sounds like a single word ("No-wada-MEEN?") due to blurring or rushing the articulation of adjacent word syllables, thereby changing the potential open junctures between words into closed junctures.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Prosody has had a number of perceptually significant functions in English and other languages, contributing to the recognition and comprehension of speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] It is believed that prosody assists listeners in parsing continuous speech and in the recognition of words, providing cues to syntactic structure, grammatical boundaries and sentence type.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Boundaries between intonation units are often associated with grammatical or syntactic boundaries; these are marked by such prosodic features as pauses and slowing of tempo, as well as "pitch reset" where the speaker's pitch level returns to the level typical of the onset of a new intonation unit.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] In this way potential ambiguities may be resolved.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] For example, the sentence "They invited Bob and Bill and Al got rejected" is ambiguous when written, although addition of a written comma after either "Bob" or "Bill" will remove the sentence's ambiguity.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] But when the sentence is read aloud, prosodic cues like pauses (dividing the sentence into chunks) and changes in intonation will reduce or remove the ambiguity.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Moving the intonational boundary in cases such as the above example will tend to change the interpretation of the sentence.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] This result has been found in studies performed in both English and Bulgarian.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Research in English word recognition has demonstrated an important role for prosody.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Intonation and stress work together to highlight important words or syllables for contrast and focus.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] This is sometimes referred to as the *accentual function* of prosody.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] A well-known example is the ambiguous sentence "I never said she stole my money", where there are seven meaning changes depending on which of the seven words is vocally highlighted.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] For example, David Brazil and his associates studied how intonation can indicate whether information is new or already established; whether a speaker is dominant or not in a conversation; and when a speaker is inviting the listener to make a contribution to the conversation.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Prosody is also important in signalling emotions and attitudes.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] When this is involuntary (as when the voice is affected by anxiety or fear), the prosodic information is not linguistically significant.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] However, when the speaker varies their speech intentionally, for example to indicate sarcasm, this usually involves the use of prosodic features.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] The most useful prosodic feature in detecting sarcasm is a reduction in the mean fundamental frequency relative to other speech for humor, neutrality, or sincerity.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] While prosodic cues are important in indicating sarcasm, context clues and shared knowledge are also important.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] When a database of this speech was processed by computer, segmental features allowed better than 90% recognition of happiness and anger, while suprasegmental prosodic features allowed only 44%–49% recognition.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] The reverse was true for surprise, which was recognized only 69% of the time by segmental features and 96% of the time by suprasegmental prosody.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] In typical conversation (no actor voice involved), the recognition of emotion may be quite low, of the order of 50%, hampering the complex interrelationship function of speech advocated by some authors.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] However, even if emotional expression through prosody cannot always be consciously recognized, tone of voice may continue to have subconscious effects in conversation.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] This sort of expression stems not from linguistic or semantic effects, and can thus be isolated from traditional linguistic content.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Aptitude of the average person to decode conversational implicature of emotional prosody has been found to be slightly less accurate than traditional facial expression discrimination ability; however, specific ability to decode varies by emotion.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] These emotional have been determined to be ubiquitous across cultures, as they are utilized and understood across cultures.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] The prosody of an utterance is used by listeners to guide decisions about the emotional *affect* of the situation.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Whether a person decodes the prosody as positive, negative, or neutral plays a role in the way a person decodes a facial expression accompanying an utterance.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] As the facial expression becomes closer to neutral, the prosodic interpretation influences the interpretation of the facial expression.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Pell revealed that 600 ms of prosodic information is necessary for listeners to be able to identify the *affective* tone of the utterance.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] At lengths below this, there was not enough information for listeners to process the emotional context of the utterance.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Unique prosodic features have been noted in infant-directed speech (IDS) - also known as baby talk, child-directed speech (CDS), or "motherese".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Adults, especially caregivers, speaking to young children tend to imitate childlike speech by using higher and more variable pitch, as well as an exaggerated stress.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] These prosodic characteristics are thought to assist children in acquiring phonemes, segmenting words, and recognizing phrasal boundaries.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] And though there is no evidence to indicate that infant-directed speech is necessary for language acquisition, these specific prosodic features have been observed in many different languages.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] An aprosodia is an acquired or developmental impairment in comprehending or generating the emotion conveyed in spoken language.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Aprosody is often accompanied by the inability to properly utilize variations in speech, particularly with deficits in the ability to accurately modulate pitch, loudness, intonation, and rhythm of word formation.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] This is seen sometimes in autistic individuals.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Lexical prosody refers to the specific amplitudes, pitches, or lengths of vowels that are applied to specific syllables in words based on what the speaker wants to emphasize.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] The different stressors placed on individual syllables can change entire meanings of a word.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] In English, lexical prosody is used for a few different reasons.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] As we have seen above, lexical prosody was used to change the form of a word from a noun to a verb.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Another function of lexical prosody has to do with the grammatical role that a word plays within a sentence.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Adjectives and nouns of a sentence are often stressed on the first syllables while verbs are often stressed on the second syllable.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Here, adults will emphasize the first syllable, "IN", as "increase" functions as a noun.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Here, adults will emphasize the second syllable, "CREASE", as "increase" functions as a verb.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Another way that lexical prosody is used in the English language is in compound nouns such as "wishbone, mailbox, and blackbird" where the first stem is emphasized.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Some suffixes can also affect the ways in which different words are stressed.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Without the suffix, the lexical emphasis is on "AC".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] However, when we add the suffix -ity, the stress shifts to "TIV".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Phrasal prosody refers to the rhythm and tempo of phrases, often in an artistic setting such as music or poetry, but not always.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] The rhythm of the English language has four different elements: stress, time, pause, and pitch.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Furthermore, "When stress is the basis of the metric pattern, we have poetry; when pitch is the pattern basis, we have rhythmic prose" (Weeks 11).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Stress retraction is a popular example of phrasal prosody in everyday life.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Contrastive stress is another everyday English example of phrasal prosody that helps us determine what parts of the sentence are important.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Emphasizing that the STAIRS is how the man went up.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] Emphasizing that it was a MAN who went up the stairs.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] It's important to note that the right hemisphere of the brain dominates one's perception of prosody.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] In contrast to left hemisphere damage where patterns of aphasias are present, patterns of aprosodias are present with damage to the left hemisphere.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] In patients with right hemisphere lesions, they are characterized as monotonous and as lacking variety in their tone and expression.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/prosody-linguistics] They're also seen to struggle with the identification and discrimination of semantically neutral sentences with varying tones of happiness, sadness, anger, and indifference, exemplifying the importance of prosody in language comprehension and production.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] A **spectrogram** is a visual representation of the spectrum of frequencies of a signal as it varies with time.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] When applied to an audio signal, spectrograms are sometimes called **sonographs**, **voiceprints**, or **voicegrams**.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] When the data are represented in a 3D plot they may be called *waterfall displays*.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] Spectrograms are used extensively in the fields of music, linguistics, sonar, radar, speech processing, seismology, ornithology, and others.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] Spectrograms of audio can be used to identify spoken words phonetically, and to analyse the various calls of animals.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] A spectrogram can be generated by an optical spectrometer, a bank of band-pass filters, by Fourier transform or by a wavelet transform (in which case it is also known as a **scaleogram** or **scalogram**).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] A spectrogram is usually depicted as a heat map, i.e., as an image with the intensity shown by varying the colour or brightness.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] A common format is a graph with two geometric dimensions: one axis represents time, and the other axis represents frequency; a third dimension indicating the amplitude of a particular frequency at a particular time is represented by the intensity or color of each point in the image.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] There are many variations of format: sometimes the vertical and horizontal axes are switched, so time runs up and down; sometimes as a waterfall plot where the amplitude is represented by height of a 3D surface instead of color or intensity.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] The frequency and amplitude axes can be either linear or logarithmic, depending on what the graph is being used for.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] Audio would usually be represented with a logarithmic amplitude axis (probably in decibels, or dB), and frequency would be linear to emphasize harmonic relationships, or logarithmic to emphasize musical, tonal relationships.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] Spectrograms of light may be created directly using an optical spectrometer over time.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] Spectrograms may be created from a time-domain signal in one of two ways: approximated as a filterbank that results from a series of band-pass filters (this was the only way before the advent of modern digital signal processing), or calculated from the time signal using the Fourier transform.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] These two methods actually form two different time–frequency representations, but are equivalent under some conditions.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] The bandpass filters method usually uses analog processing to divide the input signal into frequency bands; the magnitude of each filter's output controls a transducer that records the spectrogram as an image on paper.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] Creating a spectrogram using the FFT is a digital process.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] Digitally sampled data, in the time domain, is broken up into chunks, which usually overlap, and Fourier transformed to calculate the magnitude of the frequency spectrum for each chunk.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] Each chunk then corresponds to a vertical line in the image; a measurement of magnitude versus frequency for a specific moment in time (the midpoint of the chunk).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] These spectrums or time plots are then "laid side by side" to form the image or a three-dimensional surface, or slightly overlapped in various ways, i.e. windowing.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] This process essentially corresponds to computing the squared magnitude of the short-time Fourier transform (STFT) of the signal $s(t)$ — that is, for a window width $\omega$ , $\mathrm {spectrogram} (t,\omega )=\left|\mathrm {STFT} (t,\omega )\right|^{2}$ .
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] From the formula above, it appears that a spectrogram contains no information about the exact, or even approximate, phase of the signal that it represents.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] For this reason, it is not possible to reverse the process and generate a copy of the original signal from a spectrogram, though in situations where the exact initial phase is unimportant it may be possible to generate a useful approximation of the original signal.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] The Analysis & Resynthesis Sound Spectrograph is an example of a computer program that attempts to do this.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] The pattern playback was an early speech synthesizer, designed at Haskins Laboratories in the late 1940s, that converted pictures of the acoustic patterns of speech (spectrograms) back into sound.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] In fact, there is some phase information in the spectrogram, but it appears in another form, as time delay (or group delay) which is the dual of the instantaneous frequency.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] The size and shape of the analysis window can be varied.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] A smaller (shorter) window will produce more accurate results in timing, at the expense of precision of frequency representation.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] A larger (longer) window will provide a more precise frequency representation, at the expense of precision in timing representation.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/spectrogram] This is an instance of the Heisenberg uncertainty principle, that the product of the precision in two conjugate variables is greater than or equal to a constant (B*T>=1 in the usual notation).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Synthesized speech can be created by concatenating pieces of recorded speech that are stored in a database.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Systems differ in the size of the stored speech units; a system that stores phones or diphones provides the largest output range, but may lack clarity.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] For specific usage domains, the storage of entire words or sentences allows for high-quality output.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Alternatively, a synthesizer can incorporate a model of the vocal tract and other human voice characteristics to create a completely "synthetic" voice output.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The quality of a speech synthesizer is judged by its similarity to the human voice and by its ability to be understood clearly.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] An intelligible text-to-speech program allows people with visual impairments or reading disabilities to listen to written words on a home computer.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The earliest computer operating system to have included a speech synthesizer was Unix in 1974, through the Unix speak utility.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In 2000, Microsoft Sam was the default text-to-speech voice synthesizer used by the narrator accessibility feature, which shipped with all Windows 2000 operating systems, and subsequent Windows XP systems.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] A text-to-speech system (or "engine") is composed of two parts: a front-end and a back-end.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] First, it converts raw text containing symbols like numbers and abbreviations into the equivalent of written-out words.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] This process is often called *text normalization*, *pre-processing*, or *tokenization*.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The front-end then assigns phonetic transcriptions to each word, and divides and marks the text into prosodic units, like phrases, clauses, and sentences.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The process of assigning phonetic transcriptions to words is called *text-to-phoneme* or *grapheme-to-phoneme* conversion.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Phonetic transcriptions and prosody information together make up the symbolic linguistic representation that is output by the front-end.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The back-end—often referred to as the *synthesizer*—then converts the symbolic linguistic representation into sound.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In certain systems, this part includes the computation of the *target prosody* (pitch contour, phoneme durations), which is then imposed on the output speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Long before the invention of electronic signal processing, some people tried to build machines to emulate human speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] There were also legends of the existence of "Brazen Heads", such as those involving Pope Silvester II (d.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] There followed the bellows-operated "acoustic-mechanical speech machine" of Wolfgang von Kempelen of Pressburg, Hungary, described in a 1791 paper.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] This machine added models of the tongue and lips, enabling it to produce consonants as well as vowels.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In 1837, Charles Wheatstone produced a "speaking machine" based on von Kempelen's design, and in 1846, Joseph Faber exhibited the "Euphonia".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In 1923, Paget resurrected Wheatstone's design.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In the 1930s, Bell Labs developed the vocoder, which automatically analyzed speech into its fundamental tones and resonances.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] From his work on the vocoder, Homer Dudley developed a keyboard-operated voice-synthesizer called The Voder (Voice Demonstrator), which he exhibited at the 1939 New York World's Fair.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Cooper and his colleagues at Haskins Laboratories built the pattern playback in the late 1940s and completed it in 1950.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] There were several different versions of this hardware device; only one currently survives.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The machine converts pictures of the acoustic patterns of speech in the form of a spectrogram back into sound.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Using this device, Alvin Liberman and colleagues discovered acoustic cues for the perception of phonetic segments (consonants and vowels).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The first computer-based speech-synthesis systems originated in the late 1950s.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Noriko Umeda *et al.* developed the first general English text-to-speech system in 1968, at the Electrotechnical Laboratory in Japan.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In 1961, physicist John Larry Kelly, Jr and his colleague Louis Gerstman used an IBM 7090 computer to synthesize speech, an event among the most prominent in the history of Bell Labs.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Kelly's voice recorder synthesizer (vocoder) recreated the song "Daisy Bell", with musical accompaniment from Max Mathews.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Clarke was visiting his friend and colleague John Pierce at the Bell Labs Murray Hill facility.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Clarke was so impressed by the demonstration that he used it in the climactic scene of his screenplay for his novel *2001: A Space Odyssey*, where the HAL 9000 computer sings the same song as astronaut Dave Bowman puts it to sleep.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Despite the success of purely electronic speech synthesis, research into mechanical speech-synthesizers continues.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Linear predictive coding (LPC), a form of speech coding, began development with the work of Fumitada Itakura of Nagoya University and Shuzo Saito of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) in 1966.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Further developments in LPC technology were made by Bishnu S.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Schroeder at Bell Labs during the 1970s.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] LPC was later the basis for early speech synthesizer chips, such as the Texas Instruments LPC Speech Chips used in the Speak & Spell toys from 1978.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In 1975, Fumitada Itakura developed the line spectral pairs (LSP) method for high-compression speech coding, while at NTT.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] From 1975 to 1981, Itakura studied problems in speech analysis and synthesis based on the LSP method.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In 1980, his team developed an LSP-based speech synthesizer chip.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] LSP is an important technology for speech synthesis and coding, and in the 1990s was adopted by almost all international speech coding standards as an essential component, contributing to the enhancement of digital speech communication over mobile channels and the internet.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In 1975, MUSA was released, and was one of the first Speech Synthesis systems.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] It consisted of a stand-alone computer hardware and a specialized software that enabled it to read Italian.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] A second version, released in 1978, was also able to sing Italian in an "a cappella" style.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Dominant systems in the 1980s and 1990s were the DECtalk system, based largely on the work of Dennis Klatt at MIT, and the Bell Labs system; the latter was one of the first multilingual language-independent systems, making extensive use of natural language processing methods.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Handheld electronics featuring speech synthesis began emerging in the 1970s.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] One of the first was the Telesensory Systems Inc.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] (TSI) *Speech+* portable calculator for the blind in 1976.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Other devices had primarily educational purposes, such as the Speak & Spell toy produced by Texas Instruments in 1978.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Fidelity released a speaking version of its electronic chess computer in 1979.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The first video game to feature speech synthesis was the 1980 shoot 'em up arcade game, *Stratovox* (known in Japan as *Speak & Rescue*), from Sun Electronics.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The first personal computer game with speech synthesis was *Manbiki Shoujo* (*Shoplifting Girl*), released in 1980 for the PET 2001, for which the game's developer, Hiroshi Suzuki, developed a "*zero cross*" programming technique to produce a synthesized speech waveform.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Another early example, the arcade version of *Berzerk*, also dates from 1980.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The Milton Bradley Company produced the first multi-player electronic game using voice synthesis, *Milton*, in the same year.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In 1976, Computalker Consultants released their CT-1 Speech Synthesizer.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Lloyd Rice and Jim Cooper, it was an analog synthesizer built to work with microcomputers using the S-100 bus standard.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Synthesized voices typically sounded male until 1990, when Ann Syrdal, at AT&T Bell Laboratories, created a female voice.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Ray Kurzweil predicted in 2005 that as the cost-performance ratio caused speech synthesizers to become cheaper and more accessible, more people would benefit from the use of text-to-speech programs.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In September 2016, DeepMind released WaveNet, which demonstrated that deep learning models are capable of modeling raw waveforms and generating speech from acoustic features like spectrograms or mel-spectrograms, starting the field of deep learning speech synthesis.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Although WaveNet was initially considered to be computationally expensive and slow to be used in consumer products at the time, a year after its release, DeepMind unveiled a modified version of WaveNet known as "Parallel WaveNet," a production model 1,000 times faster than the original.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] This was followed by Google AI's Tacotron 2 in 2018, which demonstrated that neural networks could produce highly natural speech synthesis but required substantial training data—typically tens of hours of audio—to achieve acceptable quality.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Tacotron 2 employed an autoencoder architecture with attention mechanisms to convert input text into mel-spectrograms, which were then converted to waveforms using a separate neural vocoder.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In 2019, Microsoft Research introduced FastSpeech, which addressed speed limitations in autoregressive models like Tacotron 2.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The same year saw the release of HiFi-GAN, a generative adversarial network (GAN)-based vocoder that improved the efficiency of waveform generation while producing high-fidelity speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In 2020, the release of Glow-TTS introduced a flow-based approach that allowed for both fast inference and voice style transfer capabilities.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The creator of 15.ai stated that 15 seconds of training data is sufficient to perfectly clone a person's voice (hence its name, "15.ai"), a significant reduction from the previously known data requirement of tens of hours.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In January 2022, the first instance of speech synthesis NFT fraud occurred when a cryptocurrency company called Voiceverse generated voice lines using 15.ai, pitched them up to sound unrecognizable, promoted them as the byproduct of their own technology, and sold them as NFTs without permission.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In January 2023, ElevenLabs launched its browser-based text-to-speech platform, which employs advanced algorithms to analyze contextual aspects of text and detect emotions such as anger, sadness, happiness, or alarm.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The platform is able to adjust intonation and pacing based on linguistic context to produce lifelike speech with human-like inflection, and offers features including multilingual speech generation and long-form content creation.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In March 2024, OpenAI corroborated the 15 second benchmark to clone a human's voice.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] However, they deemed their Voice Engine tool "too risky" for general release, stating that they would only release a preview and not release the technology for public use.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The most important qualities of a speech synthesis system are *naturalness* and *intelligibility*.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Naturalness describes how closely the output sounds like human speech, while intelligibility is the ease with which the output is understood.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The ideal speech synthesizer is both natural and intelligible.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis systems usually try to maximize both characteristics.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The two primary technologies generating synthetic speech waveforms are *concatenative synthesis* and *formant synthesis*.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Each technology has strengths and weaknesses, and the intended uses of a synthesis system will typically determine which approach is used.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Concatenative synthesis is based on the concatenation (stringing together) of segments of recorded speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Generally, concatenative synthesis produces the most natural-sounding synthesized speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] However, differences between natural variations in speech and the nature of the automated techniques for segmenting the waveforms sometimes result in audible glitches in the output.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] There are three main sub-types of concatenative synthesis.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Unit selection synthesis uses large databases of recorded speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] During database creation, each recorded utterance is segmented into some or all of the following: individual phones, diphones, half-phones, syllables, morphemes, words, phrases, and sentences.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Typically, the division into segments is done using a specially modified speech recognizer set to a "forced alignment" mode with some manual correction afterward, using visual representations such as the waveform and spectrogram.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] An index of the units in the speech database is then created based on the segmentation and acoustic parameters like the fundamental frequency (pitch), duration, position in the syllable, and neighboring phones.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] At run time, the desired target utterance is created by determining the best chain of candidate units from the database (unit selection).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] This process is typically achieved using a specially weighted decision tree.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Unit selection provides the greatest naturalness, because it applies only a small amount of digital signal processing (DSP) to the recorded speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] DSP often makes recorded speech sound less natural, although some systems use a small amount of signal processing at the point of concatenation to smooth the waveform.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The output from the best unit-selection systems is often indistinguishable from real human voices, especially in contexts for which the TTS system has been tuned.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] However, maximum naturalness typically require unit-selection speech databases to be very large, in some systems ranging into the gigabytes of recorded data, representing dozens of hours of speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Also, unit selection algorithms have been known to select segments from a place that results in less than ideal synthesis (e.g. minor words become unclear) even when a better choice exists in the database.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Recently, researchers have proposed various automated methods to detect unnatural segments in unit-selection speech synthesis systems.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Diphone synthesis uses a minimal speech database containing all the diphones (sound-to-sound transitions) occurring in a language.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The number of diphones depends on the phonotactics of the language: for example, Spanish has about 800 diphones, and German about 2500.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In diphone synthesis, only one example of each diphone is contained in the speech database.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] At runtime, the target prosody of a sentence is superimposed on these minimal units by means of digital signal processing techniques such as linear predictive coding, PSOLA or MBROLA. or more recent techniques such as pitch modification in the source domain using discrete cosine transform.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Diphone synthesis suffers from the sonic glitches of concatenative synthesis and the robotic-sounding nature of formant synthesis, and has few of the advantages of either approach other than small size.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] As such, its use in commercial applications is declining, although it continues to be used in research because there are a number of freely available software implementations.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] An early example of Diphone synthesis is a teaching robot, Leachim, that was invented by Michael J.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Leachim contained information regarding class curricular and certain biographical information about the students whom it was programmed to teach.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] It was tested in a fourth grade classroom in the Bronx, New York.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Domain-specific synthesis concatenates prerecorded words and phrases to create complete utterances.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] It is used in applications where the variety of texts the system will output is limited to a particular domain, like transit schedule announcements or weather reports.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The technology is very simple to implement, and has been in commercial use for a long time, in devices like talking clocks and calculators.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The level of naturalness of these systems can be very high because the variety of sentence types is limited, and they closely match the prosody and intonation of the original recordings.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Because these systems are limited by the words and phrases in their databases, they are not general-purpose and can only synthesize the combinations of words and phrases with which they have been preprogrammed.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The blending of words within naturally spoken language however can still cause problems unless the many variations are taken into account.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] For example, in non-rhotic dialects of English the *"r"* in words like *"clear"* /ˈklɪə/ is usually only pronounced when the following word has a vowel as its first letter (e.g.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] *"clear out"* is realized as /ˌklɪəɹˈʌʊt/).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Likewise in French, many final consonants become no longer silent if followed by a word that begins with a vowel, an effect called liaison.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] This alternation cannot be reproduced by a simple word-concatenation system, which would require additional complexity to be context-sensitive.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Formant synthesis does not use human speech samples at runtime.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Instead, the synthesized speech output is created using additive synthesis and an acoustic model (physical modelling synthesis).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Parameters such as fundamental frequency, voicing, and noise levels are varied over time to create a waveform of artificial speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] This method is sometimes called *rules-based synthesis*; however, many concatenative systems also have rules-based components.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Many systems based on formant synthesis technology generate artificial, robotic-sounding speech that would never be mistaken for human speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] However, maximum naturalness is not always the goal of a speech synthesis system, and formant synthesis systems have advantages over concatenative systems.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Formant-synthesized speech can be reliably intelligible, even at very high speeds, avoiding the acoustic glitches that commonly plague concatenative systems.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] High-speed synthesized speech is used by the visually impaired to quickly navigate computers using a screen reader.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Formant synthesizers are usually smaller programs than concatenative systems because they do not have a database of speech samples.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] They can therefore be used in embedded systems, where memory and microprocessor power are especially limited.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Because formant-based systems have complete control of all aspects of the output speech, a wide variety of prosodies and intonations can be output, conveying not just questions and statements, but a variety of emotions and tones of voice.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Examples of non-real-time but highly accurate intonation control in formant synthesis include the work done in the late 1970s for the Texas Instruments toy Speak & Spell, and in the early 1980s Sega arcade machines and in many Atari, Inc. arcade games using the TMS5220 LPC Chips.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Creating proper intonation for these projects was painstaking, and the results have yet to be matched by real-time text-to-speech interfaces.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] For tonal languages, such as Chinese or Taiwanese language, there are different levels of tone sandhi required and sometimes the output of speech synthesizer may result in the mistakes of tone sandhi.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Articulatory synthesis consists of computational techniques for synthesizing speech based on models of the human vocal tract and the articulation processes occurring there.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The first articulatory synthesizer regularly used for laboratory experiments was developed at Haskins Laboratories in the mid-1970s by Philip Rubin, Tom Baer, and Paul Mermelstein.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] This synthesizer, known as ASY, was based on vocal tract models developed at Bell Laboratories in the 1960s and 1970s by Paul Mermelstein, Cecil Coker, and colleagues.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Until recently, articulatory synthesis models have not been incorporated into commercial speech synthesis systems.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] A notable exception is the NeXT-based system originally developed and marketed by Trillium Sound Research, a spin-off company of the University of Calgary, where much of the original research was conducted.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Following the demise of the various incarnations of NeXT (started by Steve Jobs in the late 1980s and merged with Apple Computer in 1997), the Trillium software was published under the GNU General Public License, with work continuing as gnuspeech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The system, first marketed in 1994, provides full articulatory-based text-to-speech conversion using a waveguide or transmission-line analog of the human oral and nasal tracts controlled by Carré's "distinctive region model".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] More recent synthesizers, developed by Jorge C.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Lucero and colleagues, incorporate models of vocal fold biomechanics, glottal aerodynamics and acoustic wave propagation in the bronchi, trachea, nasal and oral cavities, and thus constitute full systems of physics-based speech simulation.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] HMM-based synthesis is a synthesis method based on hidden Markov models, also called Statistical Parametric Synthesis.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In this system, the frequency spectrum (vocal tract), fundamental frequency (voice source), and duration (prosody) of speech are modeled simultaneously by HMMs.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Speech waveforms are generated from HMMs themselves based on the maximum likelihood criterion.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Sinewave synthesis is a technique for synthesizing speech by replacing the formants (main bands of energy) with pure tone whistles.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Deep learning speech synthesis uses deep neural networks (DNN) to produce artificial speech from text (text-to-speech) or spectrum (vocoder).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The deep neural networks are trained using a large amount of recorded speech and, in the case of a text-to-speech system, the associated labels and/or input text.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Audio deepfake technology, also referred to as voice cloning or deepfake audio, is an application of artificial intelligence designed to generate speech that convincingly mimics specific individuals, often synthesizing phrases or sentences they have never spoken.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Initially developed with the intent to enhance various aspects of human life, it has practical applications such as generating audiobooks and assisting individuals who have lost their voices due to medical conditions.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Additionally, it has commercial uses, including the creation of personalized digital assistants, natural-sounding text-to-speech systems, and advanced speech translation services.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] As with other forms of deepfakes, audio deepfakes have faced criticism for their use in scams, phishing, and misinformation campaigns.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In 2023, VICE reporter Joseph Cox published findings that he had recorded five minutes of himself talking and then used a tool developed by ElevenLabs to create voice deepfakes that defeated a bank's voice-authentication system.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The process of normalizing text is rarely straightforward.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Texts are full of heteronyms, numbers, and abbreviations that all require expansion into a phonetic representation.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] There are many spellings in English which are pronounced differently based on context.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] For example, "My latest project is to learn how to better project my voice" contains two pronunciations of "project".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Most text-to-speech (TTS) systems do not generate semantic representations of their input texts, as processes for doing so are unreliable, poorly understood, and computationally ineffective.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] As a result, various heuristic techniques are used to guess the proper way to disambiguate homographs, like examining neighboring words and using statistics about frequency of occurrence.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Recently TTS systems have begun to use HMMs (discussed above) to generate "parts of speech" to aid in disambiguating homographs.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] This technique is quite successful for many cases such as whether "read" should be pronounced as "red" implying past tense, or as "reed" implying present tense.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Typical error rates when using HMMs in this fashion are usually below five percent.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] These techniques also work well for most European languages, although access to required training corpora is frequently difficult in these languages.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Deciding how to convert numbers is another problem that TTS systems have to address.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] It is a simple programming challenge to convert a number into words (at least in English), like "1325" becoming "one thousand three hundred twenty-five".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] However, numbers occur in many different contexts; "1325" may also be read as "one three two five", "thirteen twenty-five" or "thirteen hundred and twenty five".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] A TTS system can often infer how to expand a number based on surrounding words, numbers, and punctuation, and sometimes the system provides a way to specify the context if it is ambiguous.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Roman numerals can also be read differently depending on context.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] For example, "Henry VIII" reads as "Henry the Eighth", while "Chapter VIII" reads as "Chapter Eight".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Similarly, abbreviations can be ambiguous.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] For example, the abbreviation "in" for "inches" must be differentiated from the word "in", and the address "12 St John St." uses the same abbreviation for both "Saint" and "Street".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] TTS systems with intelligent front ends can make educated guesses about ambiguous abbreviations, while others provide the same result in all cases, resulting in nonsensical (and sometimes comical) outputs, such as "Ulysses S.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Grant" being rendered as "Ulysses South Grant".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis systems use two basic approaches to determine the pronunciation of a word based on its spelling, a process which is often called text-to-phoneme or grapheme-to-phoneme conversion (phoneme is the term used by linguists to describe distinctive sounds in a language).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The simplest approach to text-to-phoneme conversion is the dictionary-based approach, where a large dictionary containing all the words of a language and their correct pronunciations is stored by the program.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Determining the correct pronunciation of each word is a matter of looking up each word in the dictionary and replacing the spelling with the pronunciation specified in the dictionary.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The other approach is rule-based, in which pronunciation rules are applied to words to determine their pronunciations based on their spellings.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] This is similar to the "sounding out", or synthetic phonics, approach to learning reading.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Each approach has advantages and drawbacks.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The dictionary-based approach is quick and accurate, but completely fails if it is given a word which is not in its dictionary.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] As dictionary size grows, so too does the memory space requirements of the synthesis system.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] On the other hand, the rule-based approach works on any input, but the complexity of the rules grows substantially as the system takes into account irregular spellings or pronunciations.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] (Consider that the word "of" is very common in English, yet is the only word in which the letter "f" is pronounced [v].) As a result, nearly all speech synthesis systems use a combination of these approaches.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Languages with a phonemic orthography have a very regular writing system, and the prediction of the pronunciation of words based on their spellings is quite successful.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis systems for such languages often use the rule-based method extensively, resorting to dictionaries only for those few words, like foreign names and loanwords, whose pronunciations are not obvious from their spellings.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] On the other hand, speech synthesis systems for languages like English, which have extremely irregular spelling systems, are more likely to rely on dictionaries, and to use rule-based methods only for unusual words, or words that are not in their dictionaries.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The consistent evaluation of speech synthesis systems may be difficult because of a lack of universally agreed objective evaluation criteria.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Different organizations often use different speech data.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The quality of speech synthesis systems also depends on the quality of the production technique (which may involve analogue or digital recording) and on the facilities used to replay the speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Evaluating speech synthesis systems has therefore often been compromised by differences between production techniques and replay facilities.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Since 2005, however, some researchers have started to evaluate speech synthesis systems using a common speech dataset.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] A study in the journal *Speech Communication* by Amy Drahota and colleagues at the University of Portsmouth, UK, reported that listeners to voice recordings could determine, at better than chance levels, whether or not the speaker was smiling.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] It was suggested that identification of the vocal features that signal emotional content may be used to help make synthesized speech sound more natural.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] One of the related issues is modification of the pitch contour of the sentence, depending upon whether it is an affirmative, interrogative or exclamatory sentence.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] One of the techniques for pitch modification uses discrete cosine transform in the source domain (linear prediction residual).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Such pitch synchronous pitch modification techniques need a priori pitch marking of the synthesis speech database using techniques such as epoch extraction using dynamic plosion index applied on the integrated linear prediction residual of the voiced regions of speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In general, prosody remains a challenge for speech synthesizers, and is an active research topic.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Popular systems offering speech synthesis as a built-in capability.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In the early 1980s, TI was known as a pioneer in speech synthesis, and a highly popular plug-in speech synthesizer module was available for the TI-99/4 and 4A.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesizers were offered free with the purchase of a number of cartridges and were used by many TI-written video games (games offered with speech during this promotion included *Alpiner* and *Parsec*).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The synthesizer uses a variant of linear predictive coding and has a small in-built vocabulary.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The original intent was to release small cartridges that plugged directly into the synthesizer unit, which would increase the device's built-in vocabulary.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] However, the success of software text-to-speech in the Terminal Emulator II cartridge canceled that plan.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The Mattel Intellivision game console offered the Intellivoice Voice Synthesis module in 1982.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] It included the SP0256 Narrator speech synthesizer chip on a removable cartridge.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The Narrator had 2kB of Read-Only Memory (ROM), and this was utilized to store a database of generic words that could be combined to make phrases in Intellivision games.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Since the Orator chip could also accept speech data from external memory, any additional words or phrases needed could be stored inside the cartridge itself.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The data consisted of strings of analog-filter coefficients to modify the behavior of the chip's synthetic vocal-tract model, rather than simple digitized samples.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Also released in 1982, Software Automatic Mouth was the first commercial all-software voice synthesis program.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] It was later used as the basis for Macintalk.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The program was available for non-Macintosh Apple computers (including the Apple II, and the Lisa), various Atari models and the Commodore 64.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The Apple version preferred additional hardware that contained DACs, although it could instead use the computer's one-bit audio output (with the addition of much distortion) if the card was not present.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The Atari made use of the embedded POKEY audio chip.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Speech playback on the Atari normally disabled interrupt requests and shut down the ANTIC chip during vocal output.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The audible output is extremely distorted speech when the screen is on.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The Commodore 64 made use of the 64's embedded SID audio chip.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Arguably, the first speech system integrated into an operating system was the circa 1983 unreleased Atari 1400XL/1450XL computers.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] These used the Votrax SC01 chip and a finite-state machine to enable World English Spelling text-to-speech synthesis.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The Atari ST computers were sold with "stspeech.tos" on floppy disk.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The first speech system integrated into an operating system that shipped in quantity was Apple Computer's MacInTalk.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The software was licensed from third-party developers Joseph Katz and Mark Barton (later, SoftVoice, Inc.) and was featured during the 1984 introduction of the Macintosh computer.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] This January demo required 512 kilobytes of RAM.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] As a result, it could not run in the 128 kilobytes of RAM the first Mac actually shipped with.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] So, the demo was accomplished with a prototype 512k Mac, although those in attendance were not told of this and the synthesis demo created considerable excitement for the Macintosh.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In the early 1990s Apple expanded its capabilities offering system wide text-to-speech support.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] With the introduction of faster PowerPC-based computers they included higher quality voice sampling.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Apple also introduced speech recognition into its systems which provided a fluid command set.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] More recently, Apple has added sample-based voices.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Starting as a curiosity, the speech system of Apple Macintosh has evolved into a fully supported program, PlainTalk, for people with vision problems.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] VoiceOver was for the first time featured in 2005 in Mac OS X Tiger (10.4).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] During 10.4 (Tiger) and first releases of 10.5 (Leopard) there was only one standard voice shipping with Mac OS X.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Starting with 10.6 (Snow Leopard), the user can choose out of a wide range list of multiple voices.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] VoiceOver voices feature the taking of realistic-sounding breaths between sentences, as well as improved clarity at high read rates over PlainTalk.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Mac OS X also includes say, a command-line based application that converts text to audible speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The AppleScript Standard Additions includes a say verb that allows a script to use any of the installed voices and to control the pitch, speaking rate and modulation of the spoken text.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Used in Alexa and as Software as a Service in AWS (from 2017).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The second operating system to feature advanced speech synthesis capabilities was AmigaOS, introduced in 1985.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The voice synthesis was licensed by Commodore International from SoftVoice, Inc., who also developed the original MacinTalk text-to-speech system.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] It featured a complete system of voice emulation for American English, with both male and female voices and "stress" indicator markers, made possible through the Amiga's audio chipset.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The synthesis system was divided into a translator library which converted unrestricted English text into a standard set of phonetic codes and a narrator device which implemented a formant model of speech generation..
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] AmigaOS also featured a high-level "Speak Handler", which allowed command-line users to redirect text output to speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis was occasionally used in third-party programs, particularly word processors and educational software.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The synthesis software remained largely unchanged from the first AmigaOS release and Commodore eventually removed speech synthesis support from AmigaOS 2.1 onward.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Despite the American English phoneme limitation, an unofficial version with multilingual speech synthesis was developed.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] This made use of an enhanced version of the translator library which could translate a number of languages, given a set of rules for each language.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Modern Windows desktop systems can use SAPI 4 and SAPI 5 components to support speech synthesis and speech recognition.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] SAPI 4.0 was available as an optional add-on for Windows 95 and Windows 98.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Windows 2000 added Narrator, a text-to-speech utility for people who have visual impairment.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Third-party programs such as JAWS for Windows, Window-Eyes, Non-visual Desktop Access, Supernova and System Access can perform various text-to-speech tasks such as reading text aloud from a specified website, email account, text document, the Windows clipboard, the user's keyboard typing, etc.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Not all programs can use speech synthesis directly.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Some programs can use plug-ins, extensions or add-ons to read text aloud.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Third-party programs are available that can read text from the system clipboard.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Microsoft Speech Server is a server-based package for voice synthesis and recognition.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] It is designed for network use with web applications and call centers.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] From 1971 to 1996, Votrax produced a number of commercial speech synthesizer components.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] A Votrax synthesizer was included in the first generation Kurzweil Reading Machine for the Blind.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Text-to-speech (TTS) refers to the ability of computers to read text aloud.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] A TTS engine converts written text to a phonemic representation, then converts the phonemic representation to waveforms that can be output as sound.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] TTS engines with different languages, dialects and specialized vocabularies are available through third-party publishers.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Version 1.6 of Android added support for speech synthesis (TTS).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Currently, there are a number of applications, plugins and gadgets that can read messages directly from an e-mail client and web pages from a web browser or Google Toolbar.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Some specialized software can narrate RSS-feeds.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] On one hand, online RSS-narrators simplify information delivery by allowing users to listen to their favourite news sources and to convert them to podcasts.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] On the other hand, on-line RSS-readers are available on almost any personal computer connected to the Internet.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Users can download generated audio files to portable devices, e.g. with a help of podcast receiver, and listen to them while walking, jogging or commuting to work.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] A growing field in Internet based TTS is web-based assistive technology, e.g.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] 'Browsealoud' from a UK company and Readspeaker.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] It can deliver TTS functionality to anyone (for reasons of accessibility, convenience, entertainment or information) with access to a web browser.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The non-profit project Pediaphon was created in 2006 to provide a similar web-based TTS interface to the Wikipedia.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Other work is being done in the context of the W3C through the W3C Audio Incubator Group with the involvement of The BBC and Google Inc.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Also researchers from Baidu Research presented a voice cloning system with similar aims at the 2018 NeurIPS conference, though the result is rather unconvincing.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] By 2019 the digital sound-alikes found their way to the hands of criminals as Symantec researchers know of 3 cases where digital sound-alikes technology has been used for crime.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] A number of markup languages have been established for the rendition of text as speech in an XML-compliant format.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The most recent is Speech Synthesis Markup Language (SSML), which became a W3C recommendation in 2004.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Older speech synthesis markup languages include Java Speech Markup Language (JSML) and SABLE.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Although each of these was proposed as a standard, none of them have been widely adopted.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis markup languages are distinguished from dialogue markup languages.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] VoiceXML, for example, includes tags related to speech recognition, dialogue management and touchtone dialing, in addition to text-to-speech markup.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis has long been a vital assistive technology tool and its application in this area is significant and widespread.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] It allows environmental barriers to be removed for people with a wide range of disabilities.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The longest application has been in the use of screen readers for people with visual impairment, but text-to-speech systems are now commonly used by people with dyslexia and other reading disabilities as well as by pre-literate children.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] They are also frequently employed to aid those with severe speech impairment usually through a dedicated voice output communication aid.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Work to personalize a synthetic voice to better match a person's personality or historical voice is becoming available.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] A noted application, of speech synthesis, was the Kurzweil Reading Machine for the Blind which incorporated text-to-phonetics software based on work from Haskins Laboratories and a black-box synthesizer built by Votrax.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis techniques are also used in entertainment productions such as games and animations.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In 2007, Animo Limited announced the development of a software application package based on its speech synthesis software FineSpeech, explicitly geared towards customers in the entertainment industries, able to generate narration and lines of dialogue according to user specifications.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The application reached maturity in 2008, when NEC Biglobe announced a web service that allows users to create phrases from the voices of characters from the Japanese anime series *Code Geass: Lelouch of the Rebellion R2*.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] 15.ai has been frequently used for content creation in various fandoms, including the *My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic* fandom, the *Team Fortress 2* fandom, the *Portal* fandom, and the *SpongeBob SquarePants* fandom.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Text-to-speech for disability and impaired communication aids have become widely available.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Text-to-speech is also finding new applications; for example, speech synthesis combined with speech recognition allows for interaction with mobile devices via natural language processing interfaces.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Some users have also created AI virtual assistants using 15.ai and external voice control software.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Text-to-speech is also used in second language acquisition.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Voki, for instance, is an educational tool created by Oddcast that allows users to create their own talking avatar, using different accents.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] They can be emailed, embedded on websites or shared on social media.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Content creators have used voice cloning tools to recreate their voices for podcasts, narration, and comedy shows.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Publishers and authors have also used such software to narrate audiobooks and newsletters.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Another area of application is AI video creation with talking heads.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Webapps and video editors like Elai.io or Synthesia allow users to create video content involving AI avatars, who are made to speak using text-to-speech technology.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Speech synthesis is a valuable computational aid for the analysis and assessment of speech disorders.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] A voice quality synthesizer, developed by Jorge C.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Lucero et al. at the University of Brasília, simulates the physics of phonation and includes models of vocal frequency jitter and tremor, airflow noise and laryngeal asymmetries.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] The synthesizer has been used to mimic the timbre of dysphonic speakers with controlled levels of roughness, breathiness and strain.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] In the 2010s, singing synthesis technology took advantage of the advances in artificial intelligence, deep listening and machine learning, to better represent the nuances of the human voice.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] New high-fidelity sample libraries combined with digital audio workstations facilitate editing in fine detail, such as shifting of formants, adjustment of vibrato, and adjustments to vowels and consonants.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] Sample libraries for various languages and various accents are available.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/speech-synthesis] With advancements in vocal synthesis, artists sometimes use sample libraries in lieu of backing singers.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] A **vocoder** (/ˈvoʊkoʊdər/, a portmanteau of *vo*ice and en*coder*) is a category of speech coding that analyzes and synthesizes the human voice signal for audio data compression, multiplexing, voice encryption or voice transformation.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The vocoder was invented in 1937 by Homer Dudley at Bell Labs as a means of synthesizing human speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] This work was developed into the **channel vocoder** which was used as a voice codec for telecommunications for speech coding to conserve bandwidth in transmission.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] By encrypting the control signals, voice transmission can be secured against interception.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Its primary use in this fashion is for secure radio communication.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The advantage of this method of encryption is that none of the original signal is sent, only envelopes of the bandpass filters.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The receiving unit needs to be set up in the same filter configuration to re-synthesize a version of the original signal spectrum.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The vocoder has also been used extensively as an electronic musical instrument.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The decoder portion of the vocoder, called a voder, can be used independently for speech synthesis.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The human voice consists of sounds generated by the periodic opening and closing of the glottis by the vocal cords, which produces an acoustic waveform with many harmonics.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] This initial sound is then filtered by movements in the nose, mouth and throat (a complicated resonant piping system known as the vocal tract) to produce fluctuations in harmonic content (formants) in a controlled way, creating the wide variety of sounds used in speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] There is another set of sounds, known as the unvoiced and plosive sounds, which are created or modified by a variety of sound-generating disruptions of airflow occurring in the vocal tract.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The vocoder analyzes speech by measuring how its spectral energy distribution characteristics fluctuate across time.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] This analysis results in a set of temporally parallel envelope signals, each representing the individual frequency band amplitudes of the user's speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] This set of envelope amplitude signals is called the "modulator".
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The digital encoding process involves a periodic analysis of each of the modulator's multiband set of envelope amplitudes.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] This analysis results in a set of digital pulse code modulation stream readings.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Then the pulse code modulation stream outputs of each band are transmitted to a decoder.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The decoder applies the pulse code modulations as control signals to the corresponding amplifiers of the output filter channels.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Information about the fundamental frequency of the initial voice signal (as distinct from its spectral characteristic) is discarded; it was not important to preserve this for the vocoder's original use as an encryption aid.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] It is this dehumanizing aspect of the vocoding process that has made it useful in creating special voice effects in popular music and audio entertainment.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Instead of a point-by-point recreation of the waveform, the vocoder process sends only the parameters of the vocal model over the communication link.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Since the parameters change slowly compared to the original speech waveform, the bandwidth required to transmit speech can be reduced.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] This allows more speech channels to utilize a given communication channel, such as a radio channel or a submarine cable.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Analog vocoders typically analyze an incoming signal by splitting the signal into multiple tuned frequency bands or ranges.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] To reconstruct the signal, a carrier signal is sent through a series of these tuned band-pass filters.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] In the example of a typical robot voice the carrier is noise or a sawtooth waveform.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] There are usually between 8 and 20 bands.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The amplitude of the modulator for each of the individual analysis bands generates a voltage that is used to control amplifiers for each of the corresponding carrier bands.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The result is that frequency components of the modulating signal are mapped onto the carrier signal as discrete amplitude changes in each of the frequency bands.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Often there is an unvoiced band or sibilance channel.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] This is for frequencies that are outside the analysis bands for typical speech but are still important in speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Examples are words that start with the letters *s*, *f*, *ch* or any other sibilant sound.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Using this band produces recognizable speech, although somewhat mechanical sounding.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Vocoders often include a second system for generating unvoiced sounds, using a noise generator instead of the fundamental frequency.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] This is mixed with the carrier output to increase clarity.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] In the channel vocoder algorithm, among the two components of an analytic signal, considering only the amplitude component and simply ignoring the phase component tends to result in an unclear voice; on methods for rectifying this, see phase vocoder.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The development of a vocoder was started in 1928 by Bell Labs engineer Homer Dudley, who was granted patents for it on March 21, 1939, and Nov 16, 1937.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] To demonstrate the speech synthesis ability of its decoder section, the voder (voice operating demonstrator) was introduced to the public at the AT&T building at the 1939–1940 New York World's Fair.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The filters controlled by keys convert the tone and the hiss into vowels, consonants, and inflections.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] This was a complex machine to operate, but a skilled operator could produce recognizable speech.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Dudley's vocoder was used in the SIGSALY system, which was built by Bell Labs engineers in 1943.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] SIGSALY was used for encrypted voice communications during World War II.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The KO-6 voice coder was released in 1949 in limited quantities; it was a close approximation to the SIGSALY at 1200 bit/s.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Later work in this field has since used digital speech coding.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The most widely used speech coding technique is linear predictive coding (LPC).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Another speech coding technique, adaptive differential pulse-code modulation (ADPCM), was developed by P.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Even with the need to record several frequencies and additional unvoiced sounds, the compression of vocoder systems is impressive.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Standard speech-recording systems capture frequencies from about 500 to 3,400 Hz, where most of the frequencies used in speech lie, typically using a sampling rate of 8 kHz (slightly greater than the Nyquist rate).
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The sampling resolution is typically 8 or more bits per sample, for a data rate in the range of 64 kbit/s, but a good vocoder can provide a reasonably good simulation of voice with as little as 5 kbit/s of data.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Vocoders are also currently used in psychophysics, linguistics, computational neuroscience and cochlear implant research.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Since the late 1970s, most non-musical vocoders have been implemented using linear prediction, whereby the target signal's spectral envelope (formant) is estimated by an all-pole IIR filter.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] In linear prediction coding, the all-pole filter replaces the bandpass filter bank of its predecessor and is used at the encoder to *whiten* the signal (i.e., flatten the spectrum) and again at the decoder to re-apply the spectral shape of the target speech signal.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] One advantage of this type of filtering is that the location of the linear predictor's spectral peaks is entirely determined by the target signal and can be as precise as allowed by the time period to be filtered.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] This is in contrast with vocoders realized using fixed-width filter banks, where the location of spectral peaks is constrained by the available fixed frequency bands.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] LP filtering also has disadvantages in that signals with a large number of constituent frequencies may exceed the number of frequencies that can be represented by the linear prediction filter.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] This restriction is the primary reason that LP coding is almost always used in tandem with other methods in high-compression voice coders.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Waveform-interpolative (WI) vocoder was developed at AT&T Bell Laboratories around 1995 by W.B.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Kleijn, and subsequently, a low-complexity version was developed by AT&T for the DoD secure vocoder competition.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Notable enhancements to the WI coder were made at the University of California, Santa Barbara.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] AT&T holds the core patents related to WI and other institutes hold additional patents.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] For musical applications, a source of musical sounds is used as the carrier, instead of extracting the fundamental frequency.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] For instance, one could use the sound of a synthesizer as the input to the filter bank, a technique that became popular in the 1970s.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Werner Meyer-Eppler, a German scientist with a special interest in electronic voice synthesis, published a thesis in 1948 on electronic music and speech synthesis from the viewpoint of sound synthesis.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Later he was instrumental in the founding of the Studio for Electronic Music of WDR in Cologne, in 1951.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] One of the first attempts to use a vocoder in creating music was the *Siemens Synthesizer* at the Siemens Studio for Electronic Music, developed between 1956 and 1959.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] In 1968, Robert Moog developed one of the first solid-state musical vocoders for the electronic music studio of the University at Buffalo.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] In 1968, Bruce Haack built a prototype vocoder, named *Farad* after Michael Faraday.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] It was first featured on "The Electronic Record For Children" released in 1969 and then on his rock album *The Electric Lucifer* released in 1970.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Vocoder effects have been used by musicians in both electronic music and as a special effect, along with more traditional instruments.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] In 1969, Sly and the Family Stone used it in "Sex Machine", a song on the album *Stand!*.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Other artists have made vocoders an essential part of their music, overall or during an extended phase.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Examples include the German synthpop group Kraftwerk, US funk band Midnight Star ("Freak-A-Zoid"), Stevie Wonder ("Send One Your Love", "A Seed's a Star") and jazz/fusion keyboardist Herbie Hancock during his late 1970s period.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] In 1982 Neil Young used a Sennheiser Vocoder VSM201 on six of the nine tracks on *Trans*.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The chorus and bridge of Michael Jackson's "P.Y.T.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] (Pretty Young Thing)" features a vocoder ("Pretty young thing/You make me sing"), courtesy of session musician Michael Boddicker.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] For instance, the lyrics of "Around the World" (1997) are integrally vocoder-processed, "Get Lucky" (2013) features a mix of natural and processed human voices, and "Instant Crush" (2013) features Julian Casablancas singing into a vocoder.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Robot voices became a recurring element in popular music during the 20th century.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Apart from vocoders, several other methods of producing variations on this effect include: the Sonovox, Talk box, Auto-Tune, linear prediction vocoders, speech synthesis, ring modulation and comb filter.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] Vocoders are used in television production, filmmaking and games, usually for robots or talking computers.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The robot voices of the Cylons in *Battlestar Galactica* were created with an EMS Vocoder 2000.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] The 1980 version of the *Doctor Who* theme, as arranged and recorded by Peter Howell, has a section of the main melody generated by a Roland SVC-350 vocoder.
[src:text-to-speech-synthesis/vocoder] A similar Roland VP-330 vocoder was used to create the voice of Soundwave, a character from the *Transformers* series.
